<br>
We were in a race with CW for Ragefire in SolB one day.  Rezthe (CW) was trying to get her epic and Steenky (LotD) was trying to get his.  CW beat us up to the ragefire area and were ready to attack first, so LotD backs up out of the lair and all the way down the stairs.<br>
<br>
So, CW engages, starts killing, and completely wipe out with RF left at about 10% HP.  I kept doing a /who looking for folks just to make sure they were wiped out, and once they were completely dead, we moved in and killed the mob and Steenky (LotD) looted the heart.<br>
<br>
Well a couple of days later, I spend about 2 hours talking to Therdar about the situation.  He told me that since it was a triggered spawn (IE - one party had done something which specifically made the mob - RF - spawn) - it belonged to the triggering party until they chose to stop trying - even if they had wiped out.  After talking a bit more, he explains to me that this counts for each and every triggered spawn: If you trigger it - it belongs to you.  Period.<br>
<br>
LotD was clearly in the wrong according to this rule.  Lucky for us, Haygar and Steenky (both LotD) took turns camping RF for Rezthe (CW) and got folks together from both guilds to kill him the next time he popped so that she could get her epic.  So nobody got suspended and she wound up getting her epic a few days afterwards (after we screwed them over - according to the rules).<br>
<br>
It sounds to me - and I might not be understanding the entire situation here - that DV is in the same position that LotD was in the aforementioned incident.  I might be completely mistaken, however, as I don't know all the details and I'm not as versed in the rules as the GMs are.  That is just my understanding of them - I am by *NO* means the last word at all.<br>
<br>
Hope you get him soon Bakk - shouldn't take too terribly long I hope. <p><font color="CC3300" face="verdana" size="2">
